                    "title": "Tokyo Haneda’s Excel Hotel: An Excellent Place For Planespotting",
                    "content": {
                        "direction": "ltr",
                        "content": "<p>Here at AirlineReporter we write a ton about aircraft. We write a lot about airports. We’ve dabbled in <a href=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/2020/05/riding-moroccos-al-boraq-bullet-train/\">train reporting</a>. We don’t usually publish stories about hotels. But for the right type of place, we’ll make an exception (HotelReporter?!). </p> <figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img sizes=\"(max-width: 754px) 100vw, 754px\" src=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3549-754x424.jpeg\" width=\"754\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3549-754x424.jpeg 754w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3549-250x141.jpeg 250w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3549-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3549-1536x864.jpeg 1536w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3549-2048x1152.jpeg 2048w\" class=\"wp-image-61499\" height=\"424\"></figure> <p>During a trip to Tokyo we spent a night at one of the world’s best hotels for planespotting, the Excel Hotel at Haneda Airport. You don’t have to take our word for it: the hotel is frequently named in lists of the best places in the world for AvGeeks to stay. And boy did it deliver. Watch our video report below for the deep dive, and/or read on below for more details.</p> <figure class=\"wp-block-embed wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\"> <iframe allowfullscreen src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/ZqtTJJKiVgg?feature=oembed\" width=\"500\" title=\"Tokyo Haneda's Excel Hotel: The Perfect Night's Stay for Planespotters\" height=\"281\"></iframe> </div></figure> <p>There’s plenty more to the story, read on below. </p> <span></span> <p>The hotel is located at the north end of Haneda’s Terminal 2, which primarily handles ANA’s domestic operations. Those ops lean heavily on widebody aircraft like 767s, 777s, and 787s, so there’s still plenty of big game to spot. You also get a front-row seat for Runway 34R, which handles all comers including long-haulers. </p> <figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img sizes=\"(max-width: 754px) 100vw, 754px\" src=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3517-754x424.jpeg\" width=\"754\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3517-754x424.jpeg 754w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3517-250x141.jpeg 250w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3517-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3517-1536x864.jpeg 1536w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3517-2048x1152.jpeg 2048w\" class=\"wp-image-61501\" height=\"424\"></figure> <p>Make sure you book a “runway view” room — by offering that category the hotel clearly knows it’s a place for spotters. Even though those rooms are a bit more expensive (I spent $190 USD a night) it’s nice to get a guaranteed view at the time of booking. </p> <p>Or if you’re looking to go <span>full-throttle</span> AvGeek you can book the “cockpit room” which has a full-size 737 simulator inside. Seriously. </p> <figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img sizes=\"(max-width: 754px) 100vw, 754px\" src=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/room_twin_superior_cockpit_images_1920-720-754x283.jpg\" width=\"754\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/room_twin_superior_cockpit_images_1920-720-754x283.jpg 754w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/room_twin_superior_cockpit_images_1920-720-250x94.jpg 250w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/room_twin_superior_cockpit_images_1920-720-768x288.jpg 768w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/room_twin_superior_cockpit_images_1920-720-1536x576.jpg 1536w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/room_twin_superior_cockpit_images_1920-720.jpg 1920w\" class=\"wp-image-61502\" height=\"283\"></figure> <p>We had a ton of fun planespotting during our 24 hours at the hotel. And from our experience, it’s easy to tack a night here onto any Tokyo trip. If you’re flying out of another terminal at Haneda you can take the subway or a free bus to get to Terminal 2. Comment below if you’ve stayed at the Excel Hotel Haneda, or if you know of other hotels with great airport views. </p> <figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img sizes=\"(max-width: 754px) 100vw, 754px\" src=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3538-1-754x424.jpeg\" width=\"754\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3538-1-754x424.jpeg 754w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3538-1-250x141.jpeg 250w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3538-1-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3538-1-1536x864.jpeg 1536w, https://www.airlinereporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_3538-1-2048x1152.jpeg 2048w\" class=\"wp-image-61503\" height=\"424\"></figure> <p>And if you’re looking for more from AirlineReporter’s admittedly limited hotel coverage, check out:</p> <ul> <li><a href=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/2016/10/review-night-twa-room-816-hotel/\">A night at JFK’s TWA Hotel</a></li> <li><a href=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/2018/09/laxs-h-hotel-is-a-spotters-paradise/\">Planespotting from LAX’s H Hotel</a></li> <li>From further back in the archives: <a href=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/2013/10/hotel-review-the-fairmont-vancouver-airport/\">Vancouver’s Fairmont</a> and the <a href=\"https://www.airlinereporter.com/2013/02/a-review-of-the-hilton-garden-inn-at-paine-field/\">Hilton Garden Inn at Paine Field</a> </li> </ul>"
                    },
